entry.title: Handle Control-C in debugger from Lacros test runner.
entry.content:
The lacros test runner can launch the tests in an interactive debugger.

Control-C is a common command in interactive terminal debuggers and so

should be handled only by the debugger. Previously Control-C from the

debugger would immediately tear down the entire test.



This allows proper Control-C behavior in an interactive debugger first

by ignoring these signals from the Python script itself when the

debugger is running. Second, the spawned Ash process is moved to a

separate process group to also prevent it from getting Control-C.



Control-C still works correctly in the non-interactive-debugger case

because the script is careful to clean up the spawned processes.

entry.title: Revert "[text-fragment] Attempt search for dynamic content"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 6bd222a5ff1b875ac739df526a59799ded6b6676.



Reason for revert: Likely causing recent builder failures.

Example failure: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Tests/131991/overview

Failing: external/wpt/scroll-to-text-fragment/iframes.sub.html



Original change's description:

> [text-fragment] Attempt search for dynamic content

>

> Text fragments currently perform up to two searches, one when document

> parsing completes and a second attempt when document load completes (if

> load wasn't completed at parse complete time). However, pages, often

> load content after document load, when content is "dynamically loaded".

> One popular example is Mobile Wikipedia, which adds `hidden=until-found`

> on collapsed sections in idle tasks after load. This meant

> text-fragments couldn't target pages like these.

>

> This CL attempts to make text fragments work on dynamically loaded pages

> by performing a third attempt, if needed. If all directives haven't

> matched at load time, a delayed task is scheduled for 500ms that will

> request attachment on unmatched directives. TextFragmentAnchor listens

> for relevant changes in the DOM and reschedules this task each time a

> change is made. At 3000ms it gives up and performs the search to avoid

> waiting forever.

>

> At a high level, this CL tries to separate the state tracking of actions

> performed for the first matching directive from the state tracking for

> running multiple searches. This is done by introducing a new iteration_

> enum tracking the latter.

>

entry.content:
This CL changes the test expectation that the deadline is positive when

an idle callback runs after a timer expires to non-negative (which

matches the test title). On slow or overloaded machines, it's possible

for the deadline to be reached while running the callback, in which

case the deadline.timeRemaining() will be 0 and the test will fail.

test, so this changes the assertion to greater_than_equal.

entry.title: Get currentcolor to work properly for color property for colormix
entry.content:
Color is a special case for CSS as "currentColor" is equivalent to

"inherit." This presents a problem for color-mix as it can be

self-referential, i.e:



#foo {

color: color-mix(in srgb, currentColor, green);

}



Will look to itself to resolve the currentColor, as opposed to its

parent.



The simplest way to resolve this is by grabbing the parent color in Color::ApplyValue in longhands_custom, as currentColor is not retained

in computed style.



This CL also addresses the issue of nested color-mixes in this

property by calling ResolveColorMixForColorProperty recursively. A

test has been added to WPT to this effect that should get added for

interop 2023 as well.



Bug: 1448813

entry.title: [rust] Disable linker map in host toolchain
entry.content:
The linker map is a file produced by the linker in official builds

to show the location and size of each symbol. It can be enabled

using the gn argument:

generate_linker_map = true

It's used, for example, as input to our binary size analysis tools.



Certain pre-existing assertions ensure that we only generate such

a map for official builds (plus a few others) where its results will

be representative.



In the case of a build including Rust, two toolchains are involved:

* the target toolchain, where is_official_build may be true

* the host toolchain to create host build scripts and procedural

entry.title: [text-fragment] Attempt search for dynamic content
entry.content:
Text fragments currently perform up to two searches, one when document

parsing completes and a second attempt when document load completes (if

load wasn't completed at parse complete time). However, pages, often

load content after document load, when content is "dynamically loaded".

One popular example is Mobile Wikipedia, which adds `hidden=until-found`

on collapsed sections in idle tasks after load. This meant

text-fragments couldn't target pages like these.



This CL attempts to make text fragments work on dynamically loaded pages

by performing a third attempt, if needed. If all directives haven't

matched at load time, a delayed task is scheduled for 500ms that will

request attachment on unmatched directives. TextFragmentAnchor listens

for relevant changes in the DOM and reschedules this task each time a

change is made. At 3000ms it gives up and performs the search to avoid

waiting forever.



At a high level, this CL tries to separate the state tracking of actions

performed for the first matching directive from the state tracking for

running multiple searches. This is done by introducing a new iteration_

enum tracking the latter.
